article.description:
Kevin Garnett had 19 points and 15 rebounds and the Minnesota Timberwolves held on despite a late 16-5 run by
Toronto to beat the Raptors 89-81 on Monday night.
article.headline: T-Wolves overcome lapses to keep Raptors at bay
article.linkText: Garnett two assists shy of triple-double in beating Raptors
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- The Minnesota Timberwolves started collapsing late, but their lead was big enough to hold off the Toronto Raptors. Kevin Garnett had 19 points and 15 rebounds and the Timberwolves held on despite a late 16-5 run to beat the Raptors 89-81 on Monday night. Wolves coach Flip Saunders notched his 300th win as an NBA head coach, but he wasn't pleased when his team, which appeared to be on its way to a blowout, blew a 21-point fourth quarter lead. "We didn't have the killer instinct that we like to see going down the stretch to finish them off,'' Saunders said. Garnett recorded his league-leading 33rd double-double, but his team looked flat. "For some reason we didn't have our usual energy,'' Garnett said. "We slacked off, but we were able to hold on.'' Point guard Troy Hudson returned after missing three games with an ankle injury and gave Minnesota some much-needed energy with 16 points in 27 minutes off the bench. "We were struggling with energy, but he came in and definitely gave us a spark,'' Saunders said. "He made some tough shots and changed the tempo of the game.'' Hudson, who sprained his ankle last Monday against Denver, hit a 3-pointer to spark a 15-0 run that spanned the third and fourth quarters and put the Wolves in control with a 71-57 lead. Wally Szczerbiak, who finished with 10 points, scored seven straight during the run and Gary Trent capped it off with a dunk off a miss while the Raptors struggled against Minnesota's defense, which rotated from zone to man-to-man. Toronto's Lindsey Hunter ended the run with a corner jumper, but Trent got another layup and Garnett dunked on Minnesota's ensuing possession. "We hit a cold stretch when our entire play went real flat,'' Raptors coach Lenny Wilkens said. "We were right in the game, and then we missed some shots.'' Guard Voshon Lenard, who had missed Toronto's last eight games with an injured left ankle, led the Raptors with 22 points in a reserve role while Morris Peterson and Alvin Williams each added 13. Lenard's return provided a lift, but the injury-riddled Raptors still badly miss Vince Carter, who missed his 22nd straight game. Toronto, which snapped a 12-game losing streak by beating the Timberwolves on Jan. 12, has never won at Minnesota in seven tries. Lenard hit a jumper with 4:03 left in the game to start Toronto's late run. "Things went well for me,'' Lenard said. "But the end result is all that matters and that wasn't good.'' The Raptors stayed close through the first half and much of the third. Rod Strickland, who started in place of Hudson, scored Minnesota's first six points of the third quarter to give the Wolves a 52-47 lead. But Lenard answered with six of his own on a layup and two jumpers to give Toronto a 53-52 lead with 6:56 left in the quarter. "Voshon was big for us,'' Peterson said. "He knocked down some shots, big shots, and really kind of took the pressure off of us.'' Meanwhile, the Wolves looked sluggish and confused. On a three-on-two breakaway, Strickland drove the lane and dished off to Szczerbiak. But Szczerbiak stopped under the basket and passed back to Strickland, who missed a short jumper and the Raptors scored in transition. After falling behind 19-13 in the opening quarter, the Wolves went on a 10-0 run fueled by inside baskets by Rasho Nesterovic and Joe Smith. Lenard ended the run with a 3-pointer with 1:08 left. Hudson, Minnesota's third-leading scorer, entered the game at the 5:11 mark of the first quarter. He scored eight straight points for the Wolves in the second quarter on a series of long jumpers. Peterson nailed a 3-pointer as time expired to pull Toronto to 44-42 at halftime.

Game notes
Saunders' record is 300-263. ... Wilkens missed another chance to record his 100th win with the Raptors. With Toronto's next victory, Wilkens will become only the second coach in NBA history to reach 100 wins with four different teams. Larry Brown is the other. ... Minnesota Vikings head coach Mike Tice watched the game a couple of seats behind press row. ... The Wolves got a scare in the second quarter when Garnett landed awkwardly on his right ankle after a shot and fell to the floor in pain. He left the bench for a few moments but returned. Garnett said he was fine. ... Toronto's 15 third quarter points tied a season low for Wolves' opponents.
